Aim¶

Through this project, we wish to analyse the trends in the Average Air Quality Index of London between January 2008 and July 2019.

The study will explore the following the points :-

  • The various pollutants in the air that are monitored to calculate the Air Quality Index
  • Comparison between "Roadside" and "Background" Monitors
  • Amount of pollutants in the air at different times of the day, month, and year
  • The emissions of the various pollutants from the London Boroughs

We also try to answer the following questions :-

  • How does the Air Quality Index vary over a period of 10 years ?
  • Trends in Air Quality Index depending on the time of the day, month and year ?
  • Which London Boroughs have the most emissions for the pollutants?
  • Can we group the Boroughs based on their level of pollutant emissions?

Data Used ¶

We make use of datasets available online from known sources (csv or xls files), along with scraping data wherever required. All sources can be found below for reference :-

Nature of Data¶

Data Source Nature of Data
London Average Air Quality Levels King's College London (London Datastore)
  • CSV File with AQI Monthly Averages
  • CSV File with AQI at different times of the day
What is the Daily Air Quality Index? Department for Environment Food & Rural Affairs Web Page

Guide for Monitoring Air Quality London (Jan 2018) London.gov.uk PDF File for reference

Data Description¶


London Average Air Quality Levels
This dataset includes 2 CSV Files. The first file contains information about the 5 major pollutants in the air during each month between 2008 and 2019. The second file contains the levels of the pollutants at different times of the day for each month between 2008 and 2019. Both files have data collected from 2 types of monitors (Roadside and Background)

What is the Daily Air Quality Index? (Web Page)
This webpage contains a table that has up-to-date information about the level of pollutant in the air that makes the air pollution Low, Moderate, High, or Very High

London Atmospheric Emissions (LAEI) 2016
This Excel file contains informtion about how much pollutant was emitted from each London Borough in 2016. For our analysis, we are only interested in the total emission of various pollutants, and not on the causes for these emissions.

List of London boroughs
The Wikipedia Web Page containing list of all London Boroughs. We can use this web page to extract information about the population, latitude, longitude and area or each borough.

Guide for Monitoring Air Quality London (Jan 2018)
This document helps us understand the difference between the two kinds of monitors (Roadside and Background) used to collect information about the various pollutants. It also gives us details about how the Air Pollution in London is measured. This is only used for reference purposes.

Statistical GIS Boundary Files for London
The Shape File in this dataset helps us to plot maps of London Boroughs using the Geopandas Library. This allows us to visualise multiple fatures in a graphical manner.

To get the Boundaries Between Index Points for Each Pollutant, we can scrap data from this webpage.
We need values for each pollutant (Ozone, Nitrogen Dioxide, Sulphur Dioxide, PM2.5 Particles, and PM10 Particles). This can be done by visiting their subsequent webpages and scraping the table that contains these boundary values.

Note¶

The following code is put in comments because the Department for Environment Food & Rural Affairs website often doesnt give permission to scrap the data, a lot of attempts made result in the 403 Forbidden Error that says that " You don't have permission to access /air-pollution/daqi on this server. "
So instead of using this code to get the Boundaries Between Index Points, we can use the table provided by London Datastore. This is in an Excel file and can thus be easily read by Pandas.

In [5]:
# The following code visits the webpages for each pollutant on the Department for Environment Food & Rural Affairs 
# website and scraps the table that includes the Boundaries Between Index Points for that pollutant

'''
pollutants = ["ozone","no2","so2","pm25","pm10"]

df = {}

for pollutant in pollutants:
    url = "https://uk-air.defra.gov.uk/air-pollution/daqi?view=more-info&pollutant={}#pollutant".format(pollutant)
    page = requests.get(url)
    soup = BeautifulSoup(page.content,"lxml")
    table = soup.find_all('table')[0]
    df0 = pd.read_html(str(table))[0]
    df[pollutant] = df0
df
'''

London Atmospheric Emissions (LAEI) 2016¶

We need this dataset to get information about how much pollution was emitted from each London Borough in 2016.
This excel file contains a separate sheet for each pollutant, which in turn has a table containing the borough names, the causes of emission, and the total emission value.
For our project, we are not interested in the casues of the emissions, and are only concerned with the final emission value of each pollutant.

Note: This dataset has values for only 4 polluants (Nitrogen Dioxide, Carbon Dioxide, PM2.5 particles and PM10 Particles). The data for Ozone and Sulphur Dioxide is not present.

From inspecting the data, we can see that the data for Carbon Dioxide has missing values for multiple boroughs, and thus, has missing values of the final emssions of CO2 in multiple boroughs. Therefore, we do not use this data.
We focus on our 3 main pollutants that have complete data present (Nitrogen Dioxide, PM2.5 particles and PM10 Particles)

Data Visualisation¶

Monitoring Pollutants in London¶

London has one of the worlds biggest air pollution monitoring networks. It includes nearly 100 continuous monitors. These are highly accurate and measure air quality pollutants in near real-time. Hundreds of lower tech measurements are also made using diffusion tubes. These monitors are mainly funded by London boroughs as part of their duties under the Local London Air Quality Management (LLAQM) framework. Most boroughs have at least one or two continuous monitoring stations.

Types of Monitoring Sites¶

Roadside Monitors¶

Roadside sites are within 1 5m of a busy road and ideally located at breathing height. Roadside sites are useful for identifying potential health hazards from traffic hotspots - especially those frequented by large numbers of pedestrians. Roadside monitors are usually mounted on lampposts or road signs.

Background Monitors¶

Background sites should not be dominated by one single nearby pollution source. Background sites should be at least 50m away from any of the large sources of pollution (like construction sites, flumes for gas boilers or diesel generators, petrol stations, multi-storey car parks and airports), and more than 30m from busy roads. They should also be more than 10m away from a main road and 5m away from anywhere vehicles stop with their engines idling. Quiet roads within residential areas, schools and other public buildings can be used as background sites if open space is not available.

Observation¶

  • As expected, the Roadside monitors report higher pollutant levels for pollutants like Nitogen Oxides, Particulate Matter and Sulphur Dioxide. This is obvious as these sites are near busy roads or a major source of pollution (like construction sites or petrol stations)
  • We observe that the level of Ozone is reported to be higher by the Background Monitors. This is because these areas usually have very low levels of Nitrogen Oxides, which is known to destroy Ozone in the atmosphere.

We can therefore conclude that Roadside areas (busy roads and high traffic areas) will have a high concentraion of Nitrogen Oxides, Sulphur Oxides, and Particulate Matter, but a lower concentration of Ozone.
However, Background sites (open spaces), will have higher Ozone concentration.

Observation¶

Overall, the level of pollutants in the air seem to be decreasing over the years. Each pollutant has seen a significant decrease from 2010 to 2019.

Inference¶

  • The sharp decrease in Nitrogen Oxides from the year 2016 can be attributed to the fact that it was during this time that dirty vehicles were deterred from entering the city center and cleaner vehicles were encouraged.
  • The use of coal was also reduced and there was a shift in heating and cooking sources from coal to gas.
  • The reduction in Particulate matter over the years can also be attributed to the change towards cleaner fuels.
  • The Ozone level has fluctuated throughout the years, but this is because the level of Ozone in the air is not directly impacted by human activities. It depends largely on the presence of other gases in the air and the location of the monitoring site.
  • Since Sulphur Dioxides are mainly produced due to the burning of fossil fuels, the reduced use of coal and better practices adopted by industrial plants has led to the decrease in their concentration in the air.

Comparing the level of Pollutants in different Months¶

We would like to know how the concentration of the various pollutants varies according to the months. This will tell us if there are specific times of the year when the level of certain pollutants in the air is higher, and possiblly allow us to reason why that is so.

We use the total concentration of pollutants (Roadside + Background) in the various months, and plot the values to see how the values have varied in the different years.

In [67]:

Observation¶

  • The concentration of gases like NO and NO2 peaks during the Winter Months and is much lower in the summer time.
  • The concentrations of Particulate Matter tends of peak during the February - April period
  • Ozone concentration is highest during the Summer Months
  • The concentration of SO2 remains quite stable throughout the year.

Inference and Analysis¶

We try to find out why the above trends exist.

  • Since Nitrogen Oxides are produced when fuel is burnt, the increase in burning of fuels for the purpose of heating in the winter months makes it clear why the concentration peaks during these months. Also, in winter, when the ground in cold, most emissions are trapped near to the ground and further increase the concentration of these gases in the air.

  • According to the UK Government Website, the increase in concentration of Particulate Matter during the February - April time can be attributed to the increase in burning of wood and coal by households in stoves and open fires. This coupled with the wind patterns leads to this peak in concentration.

  • Ozone pollution worsens in the summer months as a lot of the compounds that react to form Ozone, do so in the presence of sunlight, so longer days with bright sunlight act as catalysts for these reactions. Moreover, the decrease in Nitrogen Oxides in the air also contributes to the increase in Ozone, as NO reacts with Ozone (destroying it) to form further Nitrogen Oxides.

Observation¶

We would expect that Central London would have higher levels of pollution, however, our map shows us something different. This is because we have not taken into account the difference in area of the various boroughs. A borough with larger area will naturally have more pollution monitors, and will also be expected to have higher emissions of pollutants.

We can calculate the emissions per unit area of each borough and then plot the maps again to see if it is any different from these maps. Firstly, we check if our assumption actually holds or not, i.e, does increase in Area or Population actually increase in the pollutant levels?

We can plot a 3D graph of how NOx levels change with respect to change in Area or Population

Data Modelling¶

Motivation¶

We want to know if we can group the various London Boroughs on the basis of their pollution emissions, that is, form clusters of boroughs that have similar levels of pollution emissions.

We already have a dataframe with pollution emissions per unit area, however, we would like to see how the pollution level is affected per person in each Borough as well. So we can find the pollution levels in each borough per person.

Performing the Clustering¶

We use the K-means Clustering Algorithm to perform the clustering on the Boroughs. As the name suggests, the algorithm makes use of the means of the data to cluster them. Here K is just the number of clusters we want our data to be divided in. We have to choose the value of K ourselves, and there are ways in which can select the right K for our data.

I had written in short article on Medium explaining the details about K-Means Clustering, which can be viewed here.

Finding the right K value — The Elbow Method¶

The Elbow Method is one of the best ways to find out which value of K will give us the most stable clusters. The Elbow Method is based on the concept that the best value of K is the one where the Within Sum of Squares (WSS) value is the least. The total WSS measures the compactness of the clustering and it should be as small as possible. The Within Sum of squares or WSS value is defined as the sum of the squared distance between each member of the cluster and its centroid. Mathematically, this can be represented as:

Here the x values are the data points and the corresponding c values are the centroids to which these data points are assigned. We want a minimum WSS value for good clustering.

When we plot this value along with the corresponding value of k, we will observe a sharp decrease in the WSS value at some value of k. After this, the value will keep on decreasing, but very slowly. Clearly, the larger the k, the lesser the WSS value, but we don't want the least WSS value in that sense. We want a suitable value of k such that our WSS value is low and if we take any value larger than this k, the change in WSS value is minimal.

Note than, SSE (Sum of Squared Errors) can be also be used instead of WSS

Choosing the Appropriate Number of Clusters for Emission per Person¶

In [95]:
kmeans_kwargs = {
     "init": "random",
     "n_init": 10,
     "max_iter": 300,
     "random_state": 10,
 }

 # A list holds the SSE values for each k
sse = []
for k in range(1, 11):
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=k, **kmeans_kwargs)
    kmeans.fit(per_person_scaled)
    sse.append(kmeans.inertia_)
In [96]:
plt.style.use("fivethirtyeight")
plt.plot(range(1, 11), sse)
plt.xticks(range(1, 11))
plt.xlabel("Number of Clusters")
plt.ylabel("SSE")
plt.title('Finding the No. of Clusters using Elbow Method')
plt.show()

We can clearly see the elbow point at k = 3. Therefore, choosing to cluster our boroughs into 3 groups based on the emissions per person would be ideal.

Conclusion \& Results

The various pollutants in the air that are monitored to calculate the Air Quality Index¶

  • Throughout our analysis, we come across 4 different kinds of pollutant gases: Nitrogen Oxides (NO and NO2), Ozone, Sulphur Dioxide, and Particulate Matter (PM2.5 and PM10)
  • Concentrations of some of these pollutants are not independent. NO oxidises with Ozone to form NO2, therefore the concentration of NO and NO2 goes hand in hand. While increase in concentration of Nitrogen Oxides means a decrease in concentration of Ozone. This point is backed by our analysis.

Comparison between "Roadside" and "Background" Monitors¶

  • Roadside monitors report higher pollutant levels for pollutants like Nitogen Oxides, Particulate Matter and Sulphur Dioxide. This is obvious as these sites are near busy roads or a major source of pollution (like construction sites or petrol stations)

  • Ozone is reported to be higher by the Background Monitors.This is because these areas usually have very low levels of Nitrogen Oxides, which is known to destroy Ozone in the atmosphere.

  • There is no significant difference between the trend of pollution levels reported by Roadside and Background Monitors during different times of the day. When Pollution reported by Roadside monitor is high (like during peak office hours), then so is the pollution reported by Background monitors.

Amount of pollutants in the air at different times of the day, month, and year¶

  • Levels of Nitrogen Oxides were much higher during Winter Months, compared to Summer Months
  • The concentrations ofParticulate Mattertends of peak during the February - April period
  • Ozoneconcentration is highest during the Summer Months
  • The concentration ofSO2remains quite stable throughout the year.
  • Both in Winter Months and Summer Months, the pollution levels peaks at 6 am (early morning) and then late evening. This can be because this is the time when people start to go to work and majority of public transport vehicles begin operating (Office Hours).

The emissions of the various pollutants from the London Boroughs¶

  • Our analysis showed that the overall pollution level in London is Low. None of the major pollutants are present in the air in high concentrations.
  • When we compared the pollutant emissions in the various boroughs, we found no particular trend that would suggest that the pollution varies by geography. However, we did notice that boroughs with larger areas had higher pollutant emissions. This pointed us towards looking at the emissions per unit area so that we can examine the boroughs fairly
  • When we plotted the maps based on the emissions per unit area, it is clear that boroughs in central London have much higher emissions.

How does the Air Quality Index vary over a period of 10 years ?¶

  • There is sharp decrease inNitrogen Oxidesfrom the year 2016 due to the decrease in dirty vehicles in the city and lower usage of coal
  • Particulate Matter and Sulphur Dioxide have also decreased in concentration of the years due to the same reasons.
  • Level of Ozone in the air is not directly impacted by human activities. It depends largely on the presence of other gases in the air and the location of the monitoring site. Therefore, its concentration has fluctuated.

Trends in Air Quality Index depending on the time of the day, month and year ?¶

As outlined in our analysis:-

  • SinceNitrogen Oxidesare produced when fuel is burnt, the increase in burning of fuels for the purpose of heating in the winter months makes it clear why the concentration peaks during these months. Also, in winter, when the ground in cold, most emissions are trapped near to the ground and further increase the concentration of these gases in the air.
  • According to the UK Government Website, the increase in concentration ofParticulate Matterduring the February - April time can be attributed to the increase in burning of wood and coal by households in stoves and open fires. This coupled with the wind patterns leads to this peak in concentration.
  • Ozonepollution worsens in the summer months as a lot of the compounds that react to form Ozone, do so in the presence of sunlight, so longer days with bright sunlight act as catalysts for these reactions. Moreover, the decrease in Nitrogen Oxides in the air also contributes to the increase in Ozone, as NO reacts with Ozone (destroying it) to form further Nitrogen Oxides.
  • The variation in the pollution levels during the Winter Months has been more when compared over the period of 10 years. The concentration of gases likeNitrogen Oxides,SO2andParticulate Matterin the month of January are very high. However, they decrease as we progress into the summer months, but then again increase as we move towards September and the later Winter Months. The trend forOzoneis exactly the opposite.

Which London Boroughs have the most emissions for the pollutants?¶

From plotting maps based on pollution emissions per unit area, and modelling the data into groups based on the emissions per unit area and per unit person, it is clear that the boroughs in in and near Zone 1 of London (Central London) have the most emissions of pollutants. These include boroughs like Camden, Kensington, Hackney, Tower Hamlets, Islington and Lambeth.

Can we group the Boroughs based on their level of pollutant emissions?¶

  • Yes, through our analysis, we found that we can group the boroughs on the basis of 2 factors - Pollution emissions per person and Pollution emissions per unit area.
  • When grouping boroughs according to pollution emissions per person, we get 2 proper clusters and the outlier(s) are separated out.
  • When grouping the boroughs according to pollution per unit area, we get 3 proper clusters.
  • The clustering suggests that the boroughs in the centre can approximately be grouped together, and boroughs on the boundaries can be groups together. This makes sense as our analysis showed that pollution levels are much higher in the centre.
